single-region solvers
=====================

Everything that isn't conjugate heat transfer and isn't multiphase.
One fluid region, optionally with an energy equation, optionally
buoyant. These are the most-used solvers and the easiest to
contribute to.


what's here
-----------

  - simpleFoam — steady incompressible. Use for steady-state
    external aero, pipe flow, mixing problems where Mach is low and
    no heat transfer matters.

  - pimpleFoam — transient incompressible. Use for unsteady
    flows, vortex shedding, time-dependent boundary conditions.

  - icoFoam — incompressible laminar (no turbulence model).
    Use for low-Re flows, validation cases, microfluidics.

  - rhoSimpleFoam — steady compressible with heat transfer.
    Use for low-Mach compressible flows where temperature varies
    significantly (cryogenic pipe flow, hot gas systems).

  - rhoPimpleFoam — transient compressible with heat transfer.
    Use for unsteady compressible flows, transient cryogenic
    startup, time-dependent heat transfer.

  - buoyantSimpleFoam / buoyantPimpleFoam — buoyant
    compressible. Natural convection driven by density variation
    with temperature, full compressible equation of state. For
    high-ΔT or large-domain problems where Boussinesq isn't
    sufficient.

  - buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam /
    buoyantBoussinesqPimpleFoam — buoyant incompressible with
    Boussinesq approximation. Lighter-weight thermal natural
    convection — valid when ΔT/T < 0.1 ish.


what they share
---------------

  - Generated 0/* fields: U, p (or p_rgh for buoyant),
    T for energy solvers, turbulence fields for RAS models
    (k, omega, nut for kOmegaSST; k, epsilon, nut for
    kEpsilon; nuTilda, nut for Spalart-Allmaras).

  - System files: controlDict, fvSchemes, fvSolution,
    sometimes fvOptions (for energy solvers needing
    limitTemperature clamps).

  - Constant files: transportProperties (incompressible) or
    thermophysicalProperties (compressible),
    turbulenceProperties, sometimes g (buoyant).


what's special per solver
-------------------------

The plugin docs (simd_agent/solvers/<name>/prompts/_solver.md)
carry the per-solver pitfalls the validators enforce. A few that
matter in practice:

  - rhoSimpleFoam — needs div(phi,K) and div(phid,p) in
    fvSchemes. SIMPLEC + GAMG for p. h relaxation must be
    aggressive (0.05) for cryogenic cases.

  - rhoPimpleFoam isothermal — must use PBiCGStab+DILU for
    p (not GAMG). nOuterCorrectors=2. momentumPredictor yes.

  - buoyantSimpleFoam — 0/T internalField must equal
    inlet_temperature, never default to 300 K. The validator
    auto-corrects.

  - All compressible solvers — fvOptions limitTemperature
    clamps in-cell temperatures, but NOT boundary values. The
    validator clamps fixedValue T BCs to the EOS ceiling.

The current set of validators lives in
simd_agent/run/genai_codegen.py:validate_generated_files().
Future work folds these into per-plugin validate() methods.


turbulence models
-----------------

Each plugin declares which models are valid via the
turbulence_fields() method. The defaults:

  | model              | fields generated                |
  |--------------------|----------------------------------|
  | laminar / none     | (none)                          |
  | kEpsilon           | k, epsilon, nut                 |
  | kOmega             | k, omega, nut                   |
  | kOmegaSST          | k, omega, nut                   |
  | SpalartAllmaras    | nuTilda, nut                    |

Multi-region energy solvers add alphat to all RAS models — see
multi-region-cht.


examples
--------

  - examples/u-shape-pipe/ — pimpleFoam + kOmegaSST,
    incompressible turbulent water flow through a U-bend.
  - examples/z-bend/ — rhoPimpleFoam (or rhoSimpleFoam),
    compressible flow with heat transfer through a Z-bend.

Both ship the full OpenFOAM case so you can run them directly.
